Evaluation of OCR Quality of the Historic Newspaper Archive of the KB

Myriam C. Traub, Jacco van Ossenbruggen, Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica, Information Access research group

03 June, 2015

Disclaimer

This page describes work in progress. Please cite only as work in progress. For feedback and questions, please do not hesitate to contact us.

In order allow readers to comprehend how we compiled the numbers and statistics, this document was created using KnitR. Therefore, the R code we wrote is included in the document.

Introduction

The historic newspaper archive1 of the National Library of The Netherlands (KB)2 contains over 10 million Dutch newspaper pages from the period 1618 to 1995. It can be searched using full text on the OCR output, and on the meta data attributed to each item in the collection. Despite the fact that it contains copyrighted material, the archive is openly available via the Web. In addition, the library publishes all items in the archive, including the scanned images, the OCRed texts and the metadata records, under a persistent URI scheme. These factors, combined with the large number of pages and the extensive time period covered, make the archive an extremely rich resource that has already been used in many research projects3.

According to our contacts at the KB, no formal evaluation of the OCR quality has been done so far. Since the accuracy of the OCR processing directly influences the search tasks performed on the archive, we decided to perform an evaluation for a subset of the archive.

In order to do so, we collected two data sets:

  • OCRed textual data from the KB newspaper archive

  • ground truth data created by the Impact project

KB OCR Data

Our aim is to evaluate the accuracy of the OCR quality for a small subset of the newspaper archive of the KB. For this, we collected OCR texts provided by the archive.

To download the OCR texts, the following schema can be used:

http://resolver.kb.nl/resolve?urn=ddd:[ID]:mpeg21:p[page]:alto

[ID] = ID of the newspaper in Delpher
[page] = page number of the newspaper page

The data is made available in ALTO XML format, a documentation can be found on the website of the Library of Congress4.

IMPACT Ground Truth Data

In order to evaluate the quality of the OCR processing of the newspapers, we needed a ground truth data set. The dataset we used was created in the context of the European IMPACT project. The ground truth data construction process had not been completely finished at the end of the project. Therefore, it had indeed not been used in a formal evaluation of the newspaper OCR quality.

The ground truth data set can be downloaded from the IMPACT website. It contains the manually corrected text files for 1024 newspaper pages. The newspaper pages span a timeframe from 1618 to 1885. The number of newspaper pages per year can be seen here:

Unfortunately, the ground truth files have a few issues:

  • Only 265 of the ground truth files can be matched with a newspaper page in the current Delpher archive due to missing IDs.

  • The reading order of the paragraphs is not correct.

  • Some pages contain duplicate paragraphs.

  • Tables are only partially included in the ground truth.

  • Text bits that are unreadable for humans, are represented by a EURO character.

Especially the reading order and the duplicate paragraphs had to be corrected in order to be able to use the data.

Correcting the reading order

In order to correct the reading order, we wrote a script that rearranges the paragraphs according to their position on the page. We ordered the paragraphs with the leftmost coordinates according to their vertical position on the page, followed by the centered paragraphs and the rightmost paragraphs. The re-arranged files were then compared to the text files created by the OCR engine using the OCRevalUAtion tool5. The coloured errors in the output of the evaluation tool helped to spot misplaced paragraphs.

# create a list of files in the given directory
correct_gtfiles <- list.files("~/OCR/data/KB_groundtruth_correctedRO_dedup/")

So far, we have manually corrected 133 files. They serve as the basis for the following analyses. While we did our best to create error-free ground truth files, we cannot guarantee that all misplaced textblocks have been identified and correctly repositioned.

We have corrected the following files (the filenames match the filenames in the original ground truth data set):

OCRevaluation: Error Rates

As a next step, we looked at the actual error rates we obtained by comparing the ground truth data with the OCRed texts with the OCRevalUAtion tool6. This tool can be used to compare OCRed text to a ground truth data set. It takes three types of errors into account: substitutions (s), insertions (i) and deletions (d). The output of the tool is a HTML file that juxtaposes the two input texts with highlighted errors and tables presenting error rates per character.

The screenshot below shows part of the output for one of our OCR files.

At the top of the result page, error rates per page are given. Below you can see a table comparing the ground truth text (left column) with the OCR text (right column). At the bottom of the page, the error rates per character are shown.

setwd("~/OCR")
path <- "~/OCR/data/OCRevalres_correctedGT/"
errors <- data.frame(GT = character(0), OCR = character(0), WER = numeric(0), CER = numeric(0)) 
file.ls <- list.files(path)

# extract the error rates for every OCR file
for (i in unique(file.ls))
{
    # read the data from the HTML file produced by OCRevalUAtion
    evalres <- htmlTreeParse(paste(path, i, sep=""), useInternal = TRUE)
    content <- as.data.frame(unlist(xpathApply(evalres, '//td', xmlValue))) 
    errors <- rbind(errors, data.frame(content[7,], as.data.frame(content[8,]), as.data.frame(content[4,]), as.data.frame(content[2,])))
}

# rename the columns and replace commas with decimal points
names(errors) <- c("GT", "OCR", "WER", "CER")
errors$WER <- as.numeric(gsub(",",".", errors$WER))
errors$CER <- as.numeric(gsub(",",".", errors$CER))

# calculate correlation between word and character error rates
correlation.wc <- cor(errors[, c("WER", "CER")])

# visualize the error distribution as boxplot and as violin plot
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
vioplot(errors$WER, col="#67a9cf")
vioplot(errors$CER, col="#ef8a62")
boxplot(errors$WER, col="#67a9cf")
boxplot(errors$CER, col="#ef8a62")
mtext("Averaged error distributions for WER (left) and CER (right)", side = 3, line = -2, outer = TRUE)

First, we look at the distribution of page level word error rates (WER) and character error rates (CER). WER are usually higher than CER 7 and show a strong correlation. The correlation between WER and CER values in our data collection is 0.87.

The CER is computed based on the Levenshtein distance 8 between the reference text and the output text (see 9): \(CER = \frac{i+s+d}{n}\) It is possible, that the error rate exceeds 100%.

The WER is computed similarly: \(WER = \frac{i_w + s_w +d_w}{n_w}\)

The WER of the OCR files ranges between 4.07 and 77.8, with a mean of 30.07, median of 27.53 and a standard deviation of 18.2.

The CER of the OCR files ranges between 1.86 and 62.91, with a mean of 16.01, median of 10.74 and a standard deviation of 14.54.

Conclusions

We have analysed the accuracy of OCRed text that originates from digitized newspaper pages from the historic newspaper archive of the National Library of The Netherlands. Our analysis shows that the quality of the OCRed text varies strongly.

The question, what OCR accuracy could be considered “acceptable”, is difficult to answer. Holley 10 classified OCR accuracy as follows:

Good OCR accuracy       = 98-99% accurate       (1-2% of OCR incorrect)
Average OCR accuracy     = 90-98% accurate      (2-10% of OCR incorrect)
Poor OCR accuracy       = below 90% accurate    (more than 10% of OCR incorrect)

By matching our results into these categories, we see that 2.26% (3) of the evaluated newspaper pages can be rated as “good”, 44.36% (59) as “average” and 53.38% (71) must be seen as “poor”.

A considerable part of the collection of newspaper pages we have collected, is of poor quality. This affects readability as well as searchability of the OCR texts. To what extent this affects research tasks performed on this data depends strongly on the requirements of the task and will be part of our future work.
